      "content": "The Maillard reaction, including the Amadori rearrangement, is indeed influenced by the pH of the dough. The reaction rate can be affected by the acidity or alkalinity of the environment, as the pH can alter the reactivity of the amino acids and sugars involved.\n\nIn more acidic conditions, the reaction tends to proceed more slowly. This is because the acidic environment can protonate the amino groups on the amino acids, making them less reactive towards the reducing sugars. On the other hand, in more alkaline conditions, the reaction can be accelerated. Alkaline environments can deprotonate the amino groups, making them more nucleophilic and thus more reactive towards the reducing sugars.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that the optimal pH for the Maillard reaction is typically slightly alkaline, around pH 7 to 9. This is because the reaction involves the formation of a Schiff base, which then undergoes the Amadori rearrangement. In a slightly alkaline environment, the Schiff base is more stable, allowing the reaction to proceed more efficiently.\n\nWhen baking sourdough, the natural acidity of the dough can influence the Maillard reaction. However, the pH of the dough can be adjusted by adding ingredients with different",
